::code-comment{title="[P0] Client-side optimistic reconciliation ignores server ordering" body="The client applies its own op immediately, then later drops the echoed op if the `opId` matches. If another user's conflicting op arrives before that echo, this client preserves local-first ordering instead of the server's `seq` ordering and can diverge from the authoritative board state. Same-field concurrent edits are especially vulnerable here. The client needs seq-aware reconciliation or a pending-op rebase, not a blind 'skip own echo' rule." file="C:\\Users\\sahil\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\Mechanize_takehome\\client\\src\\components\\CanvasPage.tsx" start=615 end=624 priority=0 confidence=0.99}
::code-comment{title="[P1] Local edits are silently dropped while the socket is not open" body="`sendOp` mutates local state and records the op as pending before attempting to send it, but `sendWs` becomes a no-op unless the socket is already `OPEN`. Any draw, move, resize, delete, or recolor performed during startup or after a disconnect appears locally but never reaches the server, so it disappears on refresh and never reaches collaborators." file="C:\\Users\\sahil\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\Mechanize_takehome\\client\\src\\components\\CanvasPage.tsx" start=121 end=135 priority=1 confidence=0.98}
::code-comment{title="[P1] Initial HTTP load can overwrite newer websocket state" body="The canvas detail fetch and the websocket session run in parallel, and both overwrite `shapesRef.current`. If the GET resolves after `init` or after one or more live `op` messages, the older HTTP snapshot can clobber newer real-time state on this client. Gate the HTTP result so it only seeds state before websocket init, or make websocket init the sole source of initial board state." file="C:\\Users\\sahil\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\Mechanize_takehome\\client\\src\\components\\CanvasPage.tsx" start=573 end=578 priority=1 confidence=0.97}
::code-comment{title="[P2] Malformed websocket canvas IDs are not rejected cleanly" body="The pre-accept membership query passes the raw `canvasId` string into a UUID-backed query without validating it first. An invalid canvas id can raise an asyncpg conversion error before the socket is accepted, turning a bad URL into an internal error instead of a clean auth or membership rejection." file="C:\\Users\\sahil\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\Mechanize_takehome\\server\\app\\ws.py" start=202 end=226 priority=2 confidence=0.92}

**Findings**

- `[P0]` [CanvasPage.tsx](C:\Users\sahil\OneDrive\Documents\GitHub\Mechanize_takehome\client\src\components\CanvasPage.tsx#L615): client optimistic reconciliation still does not honor server-authoritative ordering. Same-field concurrent edits can leave one client with a different final value than the server and other peers.
- `[P1]` [CanvasPage.tsx](C:\Users\sahil\OneDrive\Documents\GitHub\Mechanize_takehome\client\src\components\CanvasPage.tsx#L121): local edits are applied even when the websocket is disconnected, but they are never queued or retried. Those changes are lost on refresh and never broadcast.
- `[P1]` [CanvasPage.tsx](C:\Users\sahil\OneDrive\Documents\GitHub\Mechanize_takehome\client\src\components\CanvasPage.tsx#L573): the initial HTTP canvas fetch can race with websocket init and overwrite fresher live state with an older snapshot.
- `[P2]` [ws.py](C:\Users\sahil\OneDrive\Documents\GitHub\Mechanize_takehome\server\app\ws.py#L202): malformed websocket `canvasId` values are still not validated before the UUID-backed membership query, so bad URLs can fail noisily instead of being rejected cleanly.

Sessions 1 and 2 look clean in this pass. The earlier session-1 auth-envelope and token-shape issues are fixed, and the session-2 invalid-canvas-id bug is fixed as well. The earlier session-3 cross-canvas mutation and type-mutation issues also look fixed, and session 4 is now wired into the app.

